[2] Virginia (southwest)
Date: Wed 10 Dec 2014
Source: The News & Advance [edited]
http://www.newsadvance.com/news/local/pertussis-cases-increasing-in-southwestern-virginia/article_68bc8884-8085-11e4-b9d8-d360dd5c2e53.html


A wide swath of Central and Southside Virginia is seeing an increase in pertussis, or 'whooping cough'. "We are seeing more than we would expect right now," said Haley Philips, a Virginia Department of Health epidemiologist, this week. The increase is in the department's Southwestern region of Virginia, which encompasses an area that includes Alleghany, the Cumberland Plateau, Central Virginia, Mount Rogers, New River, Pittsylvania County/Danville, Lenowisco, Roanoke, and West Piedmont.

Philips would not identify the number of cases occurring either in Lynchburg or the Southwestern region, but according to Virginia Department of Health surveillance reports, 18 Virginians died as a result of pertussis in October [2014], the most recent month for which data is available. [It is unlikely that the figure quoted was for deaths from pertussis. - Mod.LL]

None of those cases occurred in the Central Virginia Health District, which includes Lynchburg and the counties of Appomattox, Amherst, Bedford, and Campbell. Philips said Tue, 9 Dec 2014, that "pertussis is always a concern" for health departments. Pertussis is one of a number of diseases the health department continually monitors. Right now, Philips said, "We certainly are paying attention."

[Byline: Amy Trent]

