[3] Utah (Salt Lake County)
Date: Thu 4 Dec 2014
Source: The Salt Lake Tribune [edited]
http://www.sltrib.com/news/1908090-155/east-high-school-fighting-whooping-cough


Seven East High School students were kept home from school on Thu 4 Dec 2014, while school officials and the Salt Lake County Health Department worked to contain an outbreak of whooping cough. The school also conducted on-site immunizations for roughly 30 students who had not yet received pertussis, or whooping cough, vaccinations, East High School Principal Paul Sagers said. "We've personally called every student who has not been immunized," Sagers said. "We have basically told them that they need to be immunized." The school's quick reaction to contain the cluster comes as whooping cough cases have declined in Utah, after a spike 2 years ago.

There have been 748 confirmed cases of whooping cough in Utah in 2014, according to Rebecca Ward, a health educator with the Utah Department of Health. That's down from 1132 at this time in 2013. In 2012, there were 1544 cases.

Unlike the cold or flu, which peak during the winter season, pertussis circulates throughout the year, said Ward. Schools in Weber County and Sevier County were hit with outbreaks in February and May 2014. "It's not as high as it has been and that's a good thing," Ward said. "We're probably not going to get to 1000 cases by the end of 2014."

Salt Lake County health officials were told of the 1st case of whooping cough 2 weeks ago, department spokeswoman Pamela Davenport said. As of Thu 4 Dec 2014, there were 6 confirmed cases, Davenport said, enough to classify as an outbreak under CDC guidelines.

[Byline: Benjamin Wood]

