[4] Nebraska (Otoe County)
Date: Fri 5 Dec 2014
Source: KMA Land [edited]
http://www.kmaland.com/news/pertussis-reported-in-nebraska-city-syracuse-schools/article_e78a6a24-7c9c-11e4-b09a-475e91448e11.html


Parents of 2 southeast Nebraska school districts are on alert regarding the whooping cough. Within the past week, students in the Nebraska City and Syracuse districts [Otoe County] have contracted pertussis. Nebraska City School Superintendent Dr Jeff Edwards tells KMA News reports were received from students at Nebraska City Middle School and Hayward Elementary School. Edwards says school officials worked with the Southeast District Health Department to inform students and parents about the illnesses.

"Through the health department," said Edwards, "we received a letter from them, and then a fax sheet, that we mailed out to all of our parents in the middle school and at Hayward. Basically, that fact sheet talked about what parents should look for, what are some of the symptoms of the whooping cough, and if their child has not received immunization, how they can go about doing that." Edwards says it's hard to tell how many students contracted whooping cough.

"There's a lot of crud going around out there," he said. "Whether it's from the pertussis or whooping cough, or whether it's from the general flu, I would say our numbers (of absences) are typical for this time of year. Anytime you've got weekends where it's 60 deg F [15.5 deg C], and the next day, it's 20 [deg F/-6.6 deg C], wearing a jacket and not wearing a jacket, there's all kinds of different factors out there."

[Byline: Mike Peterson]

